    "query": "SPP valid resource types asset registration resource types list 'resource type' 'asset registration' 'SPP'",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "SPP",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": 2000,
      "year_end": 2026,
      "range_type": "between"
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "a87bdb11-60b7-4c48-a8de-a987eb290c97",
        "score": 0.52056944,
        "text": "This document page from the \"SPP 2012 State of the Market Report\" covers two main topics: Ramp and Capacity, and Resource Utilization by Status.\n\n1. Ramp and Capacity:\n- The section discusses the ramp rates in the SPP EIS Market, which are shown in Figure II.21.\n- Ramp is standardized by available capacity and compared to average online capacity.\n- The total system ramp showed an upward trend in 2012.\n- Monthly values reveal a cyclical pattern of available ramp.\n- Peaking units used during summer peak periods generally have higher ramp rates.\n- The long-term trend is upward, contributing positively to reducing ramp breaches since the market's inception.\n- Figure II.21 includes two charts: one showing monthly ramp and average online capacity for 2011 and 2012, and another showing annual ramp and capacity from 2007 to 2012.\n\n2. Resource Utilization by Status:\n- Market participants can modify how a resource functions by selecting a status type.\n- The \"Available\" status is unique in allowing full utilization of a resource, enabling it to change output and set system price.\n- Available units are crucial for resolving congestion, alleviating operational constraints, and achieving least-cost market dispatch.\n- Resources with statuses other than Available cannot be directed by the market system.\n- Other status types include manual, self-scheduled, unavailable, and supplemental.\n- Manual status was discontinued in late February 2011 and replaced with options such as Exigent Conditions, Intermittent, Qualifying Facility, Quick Start, Shut Down, and Start.\n\nOverall, the page provides insights into system ramp trends and the operational flexibility of resources in the market through status designations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2012/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "2012 State of the Market",
          "year": 2012,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f3f05aa0-0114-48ab-a523-fa8e4add3377",
        "score": 0.5048704,
        "text": "This document page provides a list of abbreviations and their corresponding full forms, primarily related to energy, power, and regulatory entities. The abbreviations cover a range of terms including chemical compounds, organizations, plans, and technical terms used in the energy sector. For example:\n\n- SO2 stands for Sulfur Dioxide.\n- SP Loss means Self-Provided Losses.\n- SPP refers to Southwest Power Pool, Inc.\n- SPS is Southwestern Public Service Company.\n- SPPT denotes Synergistic Planning Project Team.\n- STEP means SPP Transmission Expansion Plan.\n- SUNC stands for Sunflower Electric Power Corporation.\n- SWPA is Southwestern Power Administration.\n- Tcf means Trillion cubic feet.\n- TCR stands for Transmission Congestion Rights.\n- TNP is Texas \u2013 New Mexico Power.\n- TRE means Texas Regional Entity.\n- UD stands for Uninstructed Deviation.\n- UN is United Nations.\n- U/S means Under-Scheduling.\n- VRL stands for Violation Relaxation Limit.\n- WAPA is Western Area Power Administration.\n- WCI means Western Climate Initiative.\n- WECC stands for Western Electricity Coordinating Council.\n- WERE is Westar Energy, Inc.\n- WFEC means Western Farmers Electric Cooperative.\n- YAZO refers to the Public Service Commission of Yazoo City, Mississippi.\n\nThe page is numbered 101, indicating it is part of a larger document.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2009/page_106.jpg",
          "page_num": 106,
          "title": "2009 State of the Market Report",
          "year": 2009,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c1e0702e-ee51-4839-9663-4b551858ed4e",
        "score": 0.50104254,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. discusses the utilization of different status types for market resources and their impact on market operations.\n\n**Status Type Utilization:**\n- Market Participants can modify resource control parameters by selecting a status type in their resource plans, which dictates how the resource functions.\n- In 2010, there were five status types: available, unavailable, self-scheduled, manual, and supplemental.\n- In late February 2011, the \"manual\" status was discontinued and replaced with several new types: exigent conditions, intermittent, qualifying facility, quick start, shut down, start up, and testing.\n- Only the \"available\" status allows full market utilization of a resource, enabling it to adjust output and set system prices.\n- \"Manual\" status indicates uncontrollable resources that cannot set prices and are dispatched at their last known output.\n- Self-scheduled resources operate based on predetermined output levels regardless of market conditions.\n- \"Unavailable\" status means the resource is offline and not usable by the market or participant.\n- \"Supplemental\" status means the resource is offline but can come online within ten minutes.\n- Available status units are most valuable to the market as they can respond quickly to instructions, helping resolve congestion and operational constraints.\n\n**Generation by Status Type:**\n- Most generation comes from market-available resources, allowing efficient operation and resolution of constraints.\n- The \"Start-up, Shut-down, and Test\" category was introduced in February 2011.\n- Intermittent resources are gaining importance in the EIS Market, with status types separated to categorize generation properly.\n- There is a noted steady decline in self-dispatched generation.\n\nOverall, the page explains how different resource status types affect market participation, resource dispatch, and generation efficiency, highlighting changes made in 2011 to improve categorization and market operation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2011/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1559b045-448e-4ddc-bb9b-4eee4e7f26cc",
        "score": 0.48602244,
        "text": "This document page is an appendix titled \"Appendix A. Common Acronyms.\" It provides a list of acronyms along with their full forms, primarily related to the energy and power industry. The acronyms and their meanings are as follows:\n\n- SMP: System Marginal Price\n- SPP: Southwest Power Pool, Inc.\n- SPS: Southwestern Public Service Company\n- SECI: Sunflower Electric Power Corporation\n- TCR: Transmission Congestion Right\n- VER: Variable Energy Resource\n- WAPA: Western Area Power Administration\n- WECC: Western Electricity Coordinating Council\n- WR: Westar Energy, Incorporated\n\nThe page is from a document titled \"2014 State of the Market,\" specifically page 142.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2014/page_150.jpg",
          "page_num": 150,
          "title": "2014 State of the Market",
          "year": 2014,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "937dcd6b-103e-4f23-8f23-017dd8074a2b",
        "score": 0.48286062,
        "text": "This page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. 2011 State of the Market Report contains two main points:\n\n1. It is recommended that the Southwest Power Pool (SPP) revise its energy mitigation framework to also include operating reserve mitigation.\n2. There are two protocol revision requests, which were ultimately combined into a single request, aimed at addressing market power concerns identified in the Market Power Study.\n\nThe page is the final part of a section and is numbered 99 in the report.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2011/page_100.jpg",
          "page_num": 100,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a3fd538d-caab-43f9-8d69-86a260313fdd",
        "score": 0.48058027,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit discusses the distribution of 89 resource owners registered to participate in the Integrated Marketplace as of December 31, 2021. It includes a pie chart (Figure 2-2) illustrating the breakdown of resource owners by type:\n\n- Independent power producers: 56\n- Investor-owned utilities: 8\n- Cooperatives: 7\n- Municipal: 6\n- Marketer: 6\n- State agency: 3\n- Industrial: 1\n- Federal agency: 1\n- Agent: 1\n\nThe text explains that the high number of independent power producers is largely due to the inclusion of most wind producers in this category. The term \"agent\" refers to several individual resource owners who would otherwise be classified under different types such as municipal utilities, electric cooperatives, and state agencies.\n\nAdditionally, the document notes that Figure 2-3 (not shown on this page) presents the generation nameplate capacity owned by each type of market participant. It highlights that investor-owned utilities and cooperatives together own 54 percent of the nameplate generation capacity in the SPP market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_42.jpg",
          "page_num": 42,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d93089a7-ffcd-4166-ac50-27fc412c2401",
        "score": 0.47540307,
        "text": "This document page is an appendix titled \"Appendix A. Common Acronyms.\" It provides a list of acronyms related to the energy and power industry along with their full forms. The acronyms and their meanings are as follows:\n\n- SMP: System Marginal Price\n- SPP: Southwest Power Pool, Inc.\n- SPS: Southwestern Public Service Company\n- SECI: Sunflower Electric Power Corporation\n- TCR: Transmission Congestion Right\n- WAPA: Western Area Power Administration\n- WECC: Western Electricity Coordinating Council\n- WR: Westar Energy, Incorporated\n\nThe page is from a report titled \"2015 State of the Market,\" and it is page number 157.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2015/page_165.jpg",
          "page_num": 165,
          "title": "2015 State of the Market",
          "year": 2015,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6eae9d27-d055-4bfa-8c8e-eec94e6be409",
        "score": 0.47423053,
        "text": "This document page provides an overview of the Southwest Power Pool (SPP) footprint, focusing on the Market Participant footprint used for consistent methodology metrics in the report. It includes historical data for trend analysis where applicable.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- SPP is a Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) mandated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) to ensure reliable power supplies, adequate transmission infrastructure, and competitive wholesale electricity prices. SPP was granted RTO status by FERC in 2004.\n- SPP is one of nine Independent System Operators/RTOs and one of eight NERC Regional Entities. It offers services such as reliability coordination, tariff administration, regional scheduling, reserve sharing, transmission expansion planning, training, and market operations.\n- In 2007, SPP launched its real-time Energy Imbalance Service (EIS) Market, which includes participants operating under the SPP Tariff and Market Protocols. The EIS Market footprint, representing these participants' areas, is used for the report's metrics.\n- SPP is developing new markets under the Integrated Marketplace, scheduled for launch in 2014. These include:\n  (a) A Day-Ahead Market with Transmission Congestion Rights and virtual trading,\n  (b) A Reliability Unit Commitment process,\n  (c) A Real-Time Balancing Market similar to the current EIS Market,\n  (d) A price-based Operating Reserves procurement.\n\nThe page is part of the \"SPP 2011 State of the Market Report\" and is labeled as page 12.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2011/page_13.jpg",
          "page_num": 13,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ad291b99-dc50-4c07-bd4f-79e3f0b7cb6a",
        "score": 0.47370264,
        "text": "This page is from a report by the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit, focusing on market prices and costs. It briefly mentions the importance of pricing products and capacity ratings to align reliability and economics in the power generation market. The effectiveness of this pricing will influence future price signals for investment in the SPP market. It also notes that this topic is discussed in more detail in Section 7 of the report. The page is from the \"State of the Market 2021\" report and is numbered 198.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_212.jpg",
          "page_num": 212,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "809c7842-ec7c-48da-933b-b885f2aa276e",
        "score": 0.46979254,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report focuses on the SPP market footprint and its participants as of the end of 2017.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **SPP Market Footprint and ISO/RTO Operating Regions**:\n   - The page features two maps:\n     - The first map highlights the SPP market footprint in red, covering states including North Dakota, South Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, Oklahoma, Texas, Arkansas, and parts of surrounding states.\n     - The second map shows various ISO (Independent System Operator) and RTO (Regional Transmission Organization) operating regions across the United States and parts of Canada, including entities like California ISO, Midcontinent ISO, PJM Interconnection, New York ISO, and others.\n\n2. **SPP Market Participants**:\n   - At the end of 2017, there were 211 entities participating in the SPP Integrated Marketplace.\n   - These participants fall into several categories:\n     - Regulated investor-owned utilities\n     - Electric cooperatives\n     - Municipal utilities\n     - Federal and state agencies\n     - Independent power producers\n     - Financial-only market participants who do not own physical assets\n   - The document references Figure 2-2 (not shown on this page), which details the distribution of the 61 resource owners registered to participate in the Integrated Marketplace.\n\nOverall, the page provides an overview of the geographic scope of the SPP market and the diversity of its participants within the integrated electricity marketplace as of 2017.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2017/page_28.jpg",
          "page_num": 28,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

