      "published_date": "2026-02-26T06:36:21.000Z",
      "text": "# Tokenized Real Estate Markets\n\nPublished: 2026-02-26T06:36:21+00:00\nAuthor: Michael Willson\n\n## Summary\n\nTokenized real estate markets combine property ownership structures with blockchain-based issuance and transfer rails. The token is almost never a deed recorded directly on a public chain, but represents a security, a fund interest, or an LLC membership tied to a property-holding vehicle. The blockchain layer typically handles issuance, transfer restrictions, and recordkeeping. This legal claim remains anchored in traditional property and securities law. The U.S. SEC defines tokenized securities as instruments that already meet the definition of a security but are represented as crypto assets. Dubai's Land Department has launched a real estate tokenization initiative under its Real Estate Evolution Space (REES) framework, which involves the land authority itself in tokenization. This shift from platform-level token issuance to regulator-integrated market experimentation.\n\n## Story",
